Your second point is, to me, even deeper.

“We’re all heroes in our own stories. Getting them to line up is the key.”

I think there’s an important distinction there.

People don’t usually experience themselves as villains. Most experience themselves as protagonists pursuing goals they see as justified or necessary, even when those goals conflict with someone else’s.

The difficult part isn’t making everyone agree.

It’s finding shared objectives or compatible constraints despite different stories.

Think of it less like forcing everyone into one script and more like writing a play where multiple protagonists can pursue meaningful aims without every scene becoming a zero-sum conflict.

That suggests another interface—not just for memory, but for narratives.

Imagine each person’s story exposing things like:

* Goals — What am I trying to achieve?
* Values — What principles constrain how I’ll pursue it?
* Fears — What outcomes am I trying to avoid?
* Identity — Who do I believe I am?
* Blind spots — What assumptions am I making?

The challenge isn’t erasing differences. It’s discovering where those structures overlap enough for cooperation, compromise, or at least mutual understanding.

In that sense, memory modulation and narrative alignment are related. Memory shapes identity, identity shapes narrative, and narrative shapes decisions.

If I were designing your Pantheon, I’d be tempted to treat them as layers of the same architecture:

Experience → Memory → Identity → Story → Action → Shared Reality

Each layer can be revisited and refined without pretending that every person will end up telling exactly the same story. Different heroes can inhabit the same world, but the world itself becomes the common reference point against which their stories are continually tested.